column1: #Text=This project contains the code to reproduce the experiments in the paper [Neural Code Search Revisited: Enhancing Code Snippet Retrieval through Natural Language Intent](https://arxiv.org/abs/2008.12193).
#Text=It implements retrieval systems for annotated code snippets: pairs of a code snippet and a short natural language description.
#Text=Our pretrained models and datasets are hosted on Zenodo (https://zenodo.org/record/4001602).
#Text=The models and datasets will be downloaded automatically when calling `load_model`, `load_snippet_collection`, etc.
#Text=In addition, the project also implements some *code-only* retrieval models (BM25, NCS, UNIF) for snippet collections that do not come with descriptions.
#Text=The experiments in the paper are done on Python snippets, but the code preprocessing currently also supports java, javascript, and bash.

#Text=The project is developed by a research team in the [Application Platforms and Software Systems Lab](https://www.bell-labs.com/our-research/areas/applications-and-platforms/) of [Nokia Bell Labs](https://www.bell-labs.com/).

#Text=Install the tree-sitter parsers (for preprocessing the code snippets): e.g., `codesearch install_parsers python java` or simply `codesearch install_parsers` to install parsers for all supported languages.
#Text=By default, parsers are installed under the `codesearch/parsers` directory this can be customized by setting the `TREE_SITTER_DIR` variable.
#Text=Install spacy (for preprocessing descriptions/code comments): `python -m spacy download en_core_web_md`
#Text=├── codesearch          // Contains the library modules: model code, utilities to download and evaluate models, etc.
#Text=├── nbs                 // Contains examples notebooks and notebooks to reproduce the experiments
#Text=├── tests               // Contains some unit tests, mostly for verifying the code preprocessing
#Text=We provide some pretrained embedding models to create a retrieval system.
#Text=The pretrained models also expose a consistent interface to embed snippets and queries:
#Text=#### Example: Query a snippet collection with a pretrained embedding model
#Text=snippets = [{                           # a dummy snippet collection with 1 snippet
#Text=#### Example: Embed snippets or queries with a pre-trained embedding model
#Text=Below you find a table with the pretrained models.
#Text=For each model, we mention based on what information it computes a snippet embedding: the description and/or the code
#Text=| ensemble-embedder-pacs     | description + code | staqc-py-cleaned + so-duplicates-pacs-train | nbs/ensemble/ensemble.ipynb |
#Text=This project provides a consistent interface to download and load datasets related to code search.
#Text=In the table below you find which snippet collections can be loaded.
#Text=The staqc-py-cleaned, conala-curated, and codesearchnet collections are derived from existing datasets.
#Text=For staqc-py and conala-curated we did some additional processing, for the codesearchnet collections we merely load the original dataset in a format that is consistent with our code.
#Text=If you were to use any of these datasets in your research, please make sure to cite the respective works
#Text=| so-ds-feb20                                   | Mined from Python Stack Overflow posts related to data science.

#Text=Stack Overflow dumps can be found here: https://archive.org/details/stackexchange, [LICENSE](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/)                                                             |
#Text=| staqc-py-cleaned                     | Derived from the Python StaQC snippets (additional cleaning was done as decribed in the paper).
#Text=| conala-curated                                | Derived from the curated snippets of the CoNaLa benchmark.
#Text=| codesearchnet-{language}-{train\\|valid\\|test} | The CodeSearchNet snippet collections used for training/MRR validation/MRR testing.
#Text=Licenses of the individial snippets can be found in pkl files
#Text=| codesearchnet-{language}                      | The CodeSearchNet snippet collections used for the weights and biases benchmark.
#Text=Licenses of the individial snippets can be found in pkl files.
#Text=**Note**: not all of these snippets have descriptions |
#Text=Evaluation datasets link queries to relevant snippets in one of the above snippet collections.
#Text=| so-ds-feb20-{valid\\|test}      | Queries paired to relevant snippets in the so-ds-feb20 snippet collection
#Text=| staqc-py-cleaned-{valid\\|test} | Queries paired to relevant snippets in the staqc-py-cleaned snippet collection. |
#Text=| conala-curated-0.5-test        | Queries paired to relevant snippets in the CoNaLa benchmark                     |
#Text=It is also possible to load a snippet collection as evaluation data.
#Text=The descriptions will be used as queries.
#Text=Note that this only makes sense to evaluate code-only models (i.e., models that do not use the description field).
#Text=#### Example: load a snippet collection as evaluation data
#Text=The different models we implement use different kinds of training data.
#Text=Code-only models are trained on pairs of code snippets and descriptions.

#Text=For these models, the snippet collections are used as training data (of course you should never train on a snippet collection when you intent to use that load that collection as evaluation data as well).
#Text=The USE model is fine-tuned on titles of duplicate Stack Overflow posts.
#Text=You can take a look our notebooks (e.g., nbs/ncs/ncs.ipynb, nbs/tuse/tuse_tuned) to find out how the training is done/how the training data is loaded.
#Text=To download and load the title pairs from Stack Overflow duplicate posts run:
#Text=These duplicate records have been filtered to ensure that there is no overlap with the `so-ds-feb20` and `staqc-py` evaluation datasets.
#Text=To download a text file with Stack Overflow post titles tagged with Python (used for the TNBOW baseline) run:
#Text= You can run the demo notebook `nbs/demo/demo.ipynb` to quickly try out any of the pretrained models on one of the snippet collections.
#Text=To replicate the results of our paper or evaluate your own model on the PACS benchmark, have a look at `nbs/evaluate.ipynb` and `codesearch/benchmark.ipynb`.

#Text=A custom embedding model class should implement the `embed_snippets` and `embed_queries` functions (similar to `codesearch/tuse/tuse_embedder.py`, `codesearch/tnbow/tnbow_embedder.py`, `codesearch/ncs/ncs_embedder.py` etc.).
#Text=#### Example: Benchmark a model on PACS
#Text=    model_path=model_path, # one of the pretrained model names or a path to a model that can be loaded with `codesearch.utils.load_model`
